## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

### Pattern: **Timeout enforcement** via `Thread.Abort`

In .NET 8, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`. The replacement is cooperative cancellation with `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter`.

---

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException on timeout
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }

    // Preferred: async overload
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await Task.Run(work, cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }

    // Best: pass token to work so it can cooperate
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var token = cts.Token;

        try
        {
            return await Task.Run(() => work(token), token).WaitAsync(token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

---

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Explanation |
|---------|-------------|
| **Cancellation isn't immediate** | Unlike `Thread.Abort`, cooperative cancellation only works if `work` checks the token. A CPU-bound loop that never checks `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` will keep running. |
| **`Task.Run` + `WaitAsync` doesn't kill the work** | `WaitAsync` unblocks the *caller* on timeout, but the delegate may continue running on the thread pool. This is the fundamental trade-off vs. preemptive abort. |
| **Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaking it causes timer leaks. Always `using`. |
| **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`** | Use `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` to distinguish timeout from external cancellation. |

### What was removed

| .NET Framework API | Replacement |
|--------------------|-------------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` (implicit via timeout) |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Removed entirely — no equivalent needed |
| Manual `Thread` + `Join` | `Task.Run` + `WaitAsync` |

### For truly uncooperative code

If `work` calls third-party code you can't modify to accept a token, move it to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill()` on timeout — that's the only safe way to forcibly terminate uncooperative code in modern .NET.
